<TEXT>
it had been almost a week and 
21yearold julia mendozas crying was done 
but her mother maria who had listened stoically to her 
daughters account of rape by a policeman of the national police 
could contain herself no more 
she sobbed when julia described the softvoiced rapist zipping 
up his pants and saying maybe that will make you want to 
collaborate 
allegations of mistreatment of prisoners have abounded since the 
rightist government of alfredo cristiani took office june 1 and 
began to move against what they called guerrilla fronts 
public organizations that sympathize with or support guerrilla 
positions on some or many issues 
the rebels over the farabundo marti national liberation fronts 
clandestine radio called the police animals for the alleged 
rapes 
this is too much to stand for they said the insurgents 
warned that continued repression and rights abuse will endanger a 
preliminary peace process begun last month in mexico with talks 
between government and guerrilla representatives 
just as we have been flexible and broadminded in order to 
negotiate we are likewise completely disposed to and capable of 
accompanying the struggle of the entire people and to take hold of 
the flagpole of democracy and peace and carry it forward to drive 
it into the heart of those who only want war said the rebel high 
command 
asked about the accusations maj mauricio chavez caceres head 
of the armed forces press committee said all commanders take 
pains to ensure that a prisoners human rights are respected 
because they know these people will come out of the police stations 
alleging this and that kind of abuse in order to make us look bad 
in what they called a response to escalated repression the 
guerrillas last week launched their first nationwide offensive 
since may seventyeight people were killed or wounded in the 
combat adding to the toll of a 10yearold civil war that has 
taken 70000 lives 
it was visiting day at the womens prison six miles east of san 
salvador and maria sat outside next to julia behind a backboard on 
the cement basketball court as she told her story 
julia mendoza is one of three women at ilopango jail who say 
they were raped at national police headquarters after their arrest 
the night of sept 18 following a demonstration that turned violent 
the national federation of salvadoran workers sponsored the 
march during which police were taunted by masked demonstrators 
wielding iron bars and two city buses were set afire 
authorities released 25 of 64 arrested demonstrators but seven 
women and 32 men were held 
dr roberto maldonado a forensic specialist who examined 37 of 
the 39 found corroboration of the rape allegation only in miss 
mendozas case 
the government and armed forces say prisoners like miss mendoza 
are leftist guerrilla operatives masquerading as labor activists 
and that they invent accusations of torture and abuse to slander 
authorities 
the workers federation known as fenestras by its spanish 
initials in fact espouses a political agenda identical to that of 
rebels who have waged war against a succession of usbacked 
governments 
but union and peasant organizations as well as local and 
international rights groups say the fact that an individual might 
support guerrilla positions does not strip him of the right not to 
be tortured raped or summarily executed 
maldonado found bruises cuts and scrapes on 20 of those 
arrested after the sept 18 march all said they were beaten during 
interrogation 
all said their interrogators belabored them about alleged 
membership in guerrilla units and insisted they provide names of 
cohorts 
superior court judge luis morales in charge of the unionists 
cases told the associated press that many of the injuries could 
have been inflicted with billy clubs during the suspects 
apprehension 
the new yorkbased lawyers committee for human rights after a 
fourmonth study of justice in el salvador said in a report this 
year we have identified a pattern of psychological as well as 
physical abuse of detainees 
the us state department in its 1989 human rights report to 
congress said of el salvador reports of abuse by arresting 
forces continue instances of severe beatings rape choking 
injection with drugs and electric shock were reported 
the state department said the allegations are extremely 
difficult to prove or disprove 
morales said thats because the judiciary depends entirely on 
the police forces for investigations 
we receive many allegations of rape but they never get 
anywhere he said in miss mendozas case practically 
speaking resolution would be impossible she was blindfolded and 
cannot identify the man and the same national police that are 
accused of committing the crime would be in charge of investigating 
it 
he suggested creation of a police force responsible solely to 
the judiciary to avoid such conflicts of interest 
just having an investigative arm separate from the executive 
branch would be great progress he said 
members of the treasury police were accused of raping and 
beating detainees after the april arrests of dozens of members of 
refugees organizations considered guerrilla fronts by authorities 
col rene emilio ponce chief of the joint chiefs of staff 
promised an investigation after repeated requests by the ap 
chavez caceres reported that the treasury police had investigated 
itself and found no wrongdoing 
