<TEXT>
florida has joined the growing list of 
states that withhold drivers licenses from highschool dropouts 
but teachers arent sure the change will improve education or just 
keep bad students in school 
the law which took effect sunday drew praise from some 
educators as an attentiongrabbing way to cut the dropout rate 
i believe this is an excellent tool for parents to use to 
encourage their students to remain in school said betty castor 
florida commissioner of education 
but others say the law could create a bureaucratic nightmare and 
just might cause discipline problems by keeping reluctant students 
in the classroom 
there may be more children who will be in school but they 
dont want to be in there and they may become problems in the 
classroom said mary kay cariseo of the state association of 
school administrators sometimes these children just dont care 
west virginia broke ground last year with a law requiring 
teenagers to stay in school to keep their driving privileges 
arkansas texas and louisiana followed suit and dozens of similar 
bills are pending in legislatures around the country 
rep george sangmeister dill has introduced legislation to 
make such a ban nationwide 
the florida law says students must stay in school or an eligible 
program such as a course for a high school equivalency test or a 
training program or the license will be suspended until age 18 
the state department of education estimates 9200 students will 
decide to stay in school in order to keep driving because the law 
also limits unexcused absences 11 in a row or 20 for the year 
supporters of the law say attendance might improve for perhaps 
62000 students 
nearly 30000 drop out every year in florida 
the report card on similar laws in other states is mixed 
its so new that i dont think anybody really knows all the 
effects said mary ellen parker of the national association of 
secondary school principals a lot of people simply think its 
too broad 
through february 1809 dropouts returned to school in west 
virginia but 48 percent of them then left school a second time 
said therese wilson acting director of state educational support 
services more than 780 teenagers licenses have been revoked 
under the law she said 
in florida schools across the state must certify in writing 
that each student meets the attendance rules when they apply for 
drivers licenses teenagers become eligible to drive at age 16 
many florida school administrators anticipate the law will bring 
a deluge of paperwork that could clog up the system ms cariseo 
said 
every child has got to get these forms ms cariseo said 
i think the main problem is going to be keeping up with that and 
notifying the highway safety department once they drop out 
castor the education commissioner plans to ask the legislature 
for 58 million to cover administrative costs with the funds to 
come from floridas lottery 
backers say the law will back up parents warnings about the 
danger of dropping out 
its hard to tell a student hell have a lowerpaying job when 
hes 30 and have him listen said education department spokesman 
david voss when a parent says you cant drive any more its 
immediate 
</TEXT>
