<TEXT>
jury selection got under way today in the 
liability trial in the 1987 northwest airlines crash that killed 
156 people with lawyers prepared to battle over who is to blame 
for the tragic outcome of flight 255 
the trial before district judge julian cook expected to take 
four to six months will feature about 4000 exhibits including 
shredded plane parts and hundreds of photographs 
at issue is whether northwest or the maker of the md80 plane 
mcdonnell douglas corp or both are liable in the fiery aug 16 
1987 crash 
expect a major battle between mcdonnell douglas and northwest 
trying to blame it on each other said richard schaden of 
birmingham one of five attorneys serving on a steering committee 
representing about 100 plaintiffs 
its such a hotly contested liability issue neither one will 
admit liability and thats rare schaden said 
a national transportation safety board report on the crash near 
detroit metropolitan airport said the pilots failed to properly set 
the wing flaps and slats before takeoff 
the phoenixbound plane never able to gain altitude slammed 
into an interstate 94 entrance ramp killing 154 people on board 
and two people on the ground the sole plane survivor was cecelia 
cichan then 4 who lost her parents and brother and now lives with 
relatives in alabama 
some relatives of crash victims said they would be at court 
every day betty polec an organizer of the support group flight 
255 their spirit lives on said the amount offered in outofcourt 
settlements so far has been an insult 
i want my day in court polec said my opinion is if you 
settle with the underwriter you are patting them on the back and 
saying everything is ok i want them punished 
northwest spokesman doug miller said the airline believes 
mcdonnell douglas is partially to blame in the accident 
schaden who will be responsible for arguing the case against 
mcdonnell douglas said he will discuss defects he thinks 
contributed to the crash including a disconnected or faulty 
circuit breaker on the flap and slatswarning system and an 
indicator that was supposed to tell pilots if the takeoff warning 
system wasnt working 
countered mcdonnell douglas spokesman don hanson there was no 
problem with the aircraft the aircraft is and was perfectly safe 
disagreements over liability have made outofcourt settlements 
with the relatives of victims slow in coming attorneys for the 
plaintiffs say northwest attorney carroll dubuc said in august 
that 46 cases had been resolved out of court and negotiations were 
continuing in others he didnt return repeated phone calls last 
week to his washington office 
dubuc said then that 102 suits were still pending 
i think going to trial with as many plaintiffs as we have is 
kind of unusual said jerry skinner who represents the 
plaintiffs 
northwest also has filed a suit against mcdonnell douglas texas 
instruments and national car rental saying they are partially 
responsible in the crash 
texas instruments manufactured a circuit breaker used in a 
warning system that alerts pilots when the flaps and slats arent 
set for takeoff national car rental owned a light pole that 
northwest claims was higher than the legal limit miller said the 
plane struck the light pole as it struggled to lift off at the end 
of the runway 
that suit is expected to be heard after the liability trial 
