<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether hospitals and nursing care homes may sue in federal court 
to challenge how a staterun medicaid program reimburses their 
costs 
the court said it will review a ruling that would allow a 
hospital association to invoke a federal civil rights law in suing 
virginia over the states medicaid reimbursement rates 
the attorneys general of 36 states told the court its ruling 
expected sometime next year will affect hundreds of millions of 
dollars in federal and state funding 
the virginia hospital association sued the state in 1986 
attacking the states medicaid reimbursement rates 
the lawsuit alleges that the toolow rates violate the federal 
medicaid act and the dueprocess rights of participating hospitals 
medicaid is paid primarily by the federal government but 
individual state agencies administer the program aimed at providing 
health care to the poor 
virginia officials sought to have the suit dismissed contending 
that only health care recipients not individual or associated 
health care providers have the right to sue under the medicaid 
act 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals rejected that contention 
last feb 22 in a decision that set a binding legal precedent for 
virginia maryland north carolina south carolina and west 
virginia 
acknowledging that the medicaid act does not expressly give 
hospitals and nursing care home the right to sue a state the 
appeals court ruled that the right is implied 
such suits may be filed under a muchused reconstruction era 
civil rights law the 4th circuit court said 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for virginia argued that 
congress did not intend to enable hospitals and nursing care homes 
to sue over medicaid rate disputes 
they also contended that the state should be shielded from such 
suits by immunity granted under the constitutions 11th amendment 
a friendofthecourt brief written by the oregon attorney 
generals staff and submitted in behalf of 36 states urged the 
justices to reverse the 4th circuit courts ruling 
the ruling leaves medicaid providers free to attack the 
reasonableness of each states reimbursement rates the states 
brief said every routine rate challenge may be made a federal 
case 
the case is baliles vs virginia hospital association 882043 
