the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether federal agencies sometimes must negotiate with employee 
unions over what goods and services the government buys from 
private businesses 
the justices said they will resolve conflicting court rulings in 
the contractingout dispute 
the appeal granted review today was filed by lawyers for the 
internal revenue service which contends that an agencys power to 
contract for the goods and services it needs from private industry 
is an exclusive management prerogative not subject to negotiation 
but the federal labor relations authority which adjudicates 
collective bargaining disputes between federal agencies and their 
employees ruled against the irs 
the authority said grievance and arbitration provisions of the 
tax agencys labor contract with the national treasury employees 
union apply to disputed contractingout cases the authority 
ordered the irs to bargain with the nteu over the unions proposals 
a us circuit court of appeals panel here by a 21 vote 
upheld the flra ruling last feb 28 
other federal appeals courts however have ruled that federal 
agencies have no such obligation 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the irs argued that 
the flra ruling will harm government efficiency 
under the scenario contemplated by the flra long after an 
agency has decided to contract work out and has accordingly entered 
into a contract with a private entity the agency may be told 
by an arbitrator that the contractingout decision must be 
reconsidered under the conditions that existed when it was made 
the appeal said 
that prospect is not conducive to efficient agency 
management it added 
flra lawyers told the justices that the irs case was decided 
correctly by the appeals court but the authority did not oppose 
the irs appeal 
the case is irs vs flra 882123 
