the supreme court today agreed to consider 
reinstating the murder conviction of a minnesota man who says he 
was duped into driving the getaway car in a gas station holdup 
the court said it will review a ruling that police violated the 
mans rights when they arrested him without a warrant at the house 
a where he was staying 
robert olson was convicted of murder armed robbery and assault 
in the july 18 1987 holdup of a minneapolis gas station the 
stations manager was shot to death olson was sentenced to life in 
prison plus six years 
the minnesota supreme court overturned olsons conviction last 
february and granted him a new trial ruling that he had been the 
victim of an unlawful arrest 
police acting on an informants tip did not obtain a court 
warrant or permission to enter the house where olson was staying 
before they went in and arrested him 
the fact that olson was a guest at the home did not deprive him 
of privacy rights the state court said 
noting that police said they failed to get a warrant because it 
was a sunday the state court said that is surely a curious 
reason for not observing the constitutional safeguards of 
citizens the state court also rejected arguments that police 
were faced with an emergency 
ordering a retrial the state supreme court said prosecutors may 
not use a statement olson made shortly after the arrest in which he 
admitted driving the getaway car prosecutors said discrepancies in 
the statement undermine olsons claim that he was an innocent dupe 
of the man who held up the gas station and shot the manager 
minnesotas appeal to the nations highest court was supported 
by the national district attorneys association and officials from 
10 states connecticut delaware indiana kansas michigan 
mississippi missouri new mexico south carolina and vermont 
the justices were urged to clarify whether house guests have the 
same right against unreasonable police searches and seizures as 
people in their own homes 
the case is minnesota vs olson 881916 
