<TEXT>
the supreme court today set the stage for an 
important ruling on political patronage agreeing to decide whether 
public employers may be forced to put aside partisanship when 
hiring promoting and transferring workers 
the court said it will hear an appeal by two men and a woman who 
said their job status suffered because they didnt support the 
republican party in illinois 
the court also agreed to hear a related appeal by illinois 
officials seeking to preserve patronage powers in determining when 
government workers may be laid off and rehired 
cynthia rutan franklin taylor and james moore asked the court 
to reinstate their lawsuit against illinois gov james thompson and 
state and local gop officials 
they said their rights of free speech and association protected 
by the constitutions first amendment were violated 
ms rutan said she repeatedly was denied promotions to 
supervisory positions in the state rehabilitative services 
department because she did not support republicans candidates 
taylor an equipment operator allegedly was denied an illinois 
transportation department transfer to another county because party 
officials opposed it 
and moore said the state corrections department has refused to 
hire him since 1978 because he could not get the backing of key 
republican leaders 
those who are politically favored are promoted transferred or 
hired they said those who are not so favored are not 
promoted transferred or hired 
they sued for more than 1 billion in damages and sought to 
have control of the state employment system shifted to a 
courtappointed federal receiver 
a federal judge threw out their suit and the 7th us circuit 
court of appeals by a 72 vote in february upheld the dismissal 
the appeals court relying on a series of supreme court 
decisions said public employees enjoy broad first amendment 
protection from being fired or threatened with firing but the high 
court has not extended the same constitutional safeguards to 
hiring promotion and transfer the appeals court said 
the supreme court in a 1980 ruling that significantly weakened 
the patronage system said government workers may not be fired 
solely because of their political affiliation unless that was an 
appropriate requirement for carrying out their jobs 
the 7th circuit court said employment decisions not involving 
dismissals are significantly less coercive and disruptive than 
discharges a person denied a promotion or transfer still 
retains his job and his ability to meet his financial obligations 
the appeals court said a judge should be reluctant to intrude 
into the political process and become a platonic guardian over 
state employment systems 
changes in the patronage system are better left to legislatures 
the appeals court added 
but the appeals court ruled in favor of two workers laid off 
from state jobs saying layoffs are similar in key respects to 
firings it ordered additional hearings in those cases 
the cases are rutan vs illinois republican party 881872 and 
frech vs rutan 882074 
