<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
increasing the federal governments power to keep some accused 
criminals behind bars while they await trial 
the court said it will review a ruling in a new mexico case that 
forces the government to free on bail some defendants deemed to 
be dangerous or a risk to flee before trial 
a federal appeals court said pretrial release is required even 
for a defendant who otherwise could be held in custody if a 
pretrial detention hearing is not held the first time that person 
appears before a judge or magistrate 
the justices in 1987 upheld a federal law allowing denial of 
bail before trial to people deemed dangerous to the community even 
if accused of nonviolent crimes 
before the 1984 law called the bail reform act pretrial bail 
generally would be denied only if a judge determined the defendant 
was likely to flee 
in practice however federal judges could get around the old 
law by setting very high bail ostensibly aimed at guaranteeing the 
defendants appearance in court but effectively keeping the accused 
in custody while awaiting trial 
a provision in the 1984 law states that a hearing to determine 
whether pretrial detention is justified must be held immediately 
upon the persons first appearance before the judicial officer 
unless that person or the attorney for the government seeks a 
continuance 
a federal trial judge and the 10th us circuit court of appeals 
ruled that the first appearance provision of the law had been 
ignored in the case of guadalupe montalvomurillo charged with 
possessing nearly 1 million worth of cocaine 
montalvomurillo a citizen of mexico then legally living in 
this country was stopped last february while driving a pickup 
truck near the mexican border at orogrande nm 
us customs service agents found 72 pounds of cocaine with a 
wholesale value of almost 1 million in the truck 
at a feb 16 proceeding a federal magistrate put off a 
detention hearing until feb 21 after that hearing the magistrate 
decided to release montalvomurillo on 50000 bail and other 
conditions 
government prosecutors appealed to a federal judge who ruled 
that montalvomurillo posed both a danger to the community and a 
risk to flee 
but the judge ruled that the new mexico magistrate in 
postponing the detention hearing for five days violated the 
federal bail laws first appearance rule the judge said the 
only appropriate remedy was the defendants release on bail 
montalvomurillo was freed on 88500 bail and has been a 
fugitive from justice ever since he is believed to have fled to 
mexico 
the 10th circuit court upheld the judges ruling that the only 
remedy for denying a defendant a timely detention hearing is 
release on bail even if the result of the hearing would have been 
holding the defendant without bail 
in the appeal acted on today government lawyers argued that 
automatic release for such procedural infractions is not required 
by the 1984 law 
the court of appeals erred in imposing a remedy so plainly at 
odds with the objectives of the bail reform act the appeal said 
lawyers for montalvomurillo urged the court to reject the 
governments appeal contending among other things that their 
clients status as a fugitive makes his case moot 
the case is us vs montalvomurillo 89163 
</TEXT>
