<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a 278600 
libel award against a pawtucket ri newspaper 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that news 
stories may be libelous even if they contain no false statement 
todays action sets no national legal precedent but instead 
leaves unresolved conflicting lower court rulings on the issue 
the pawtucket evening times published by a subsidiary of the 
ingersoll newspapers group was ordered to pay 28600 in 
compensatory damages and 250000 in punitive damages to dr paul 
healey a prominent pawtucket surgeon who chaired the local ymcas 
board of directors 
the rhode island supreme court upheld the jury award last march 
3 ruling that an evening times article falsely implied that healey 
was asked and refused to interrupt a ymca board meeting to help a 
heart attack victim 
jerry lampinski had gone to the boards june 23 1980 meeting to 
criticize the firings of two ymca staff members but was ordered by 
healey to leave 
lampinski then joined a group of protesters about 200 yards from 
the room where the board meeting was being held he collapsed 
minutes later 
lampinski was given first aid almost immediately and an 
ambulance arrived within 10 minutes the heart attack however was 
fatal 
an evening times article two days later reported that 
lampinskis sons were angry over the ymca boards treatment of 
their father 
the article said the family felt lampinski should have been 
given early attention by either a doctor or a paramedic at the 
board meeting 
the next paragraph said dr paul j healey is y president and 
was at the meeting when lampinski collapsed 
the following paragraph noted that lampinski collapsed 200 yards 
from where the board was meeting and the article went on to quote 
a ymca official refuting any implication that healey or any other 
board member was lax in responding to an emergency 
the official was quoted as saying that board members when told 
of lampinskis collapse also were told that the situation was 
well in hand and already being taken care of 
in its ruling rhode islands highest court said the june 25 
article that included the lampinski family criticism could have 
created the implication that healey was asked and refused to 
help lampinski and that there was enough time for him to render 
aid 
the state court added the evidence could support a finding 
that the newspaper knew these implications were false or that it 
acted in reckless disregard of whether these implications were true 
or false the defamation here really consists of what was left 
unprinted as well as what was actually printed 
using a legal definition employed by other state courts the 
rhode island court said publishing an opinion can be libelous if 
it implies the allegation of undisclosed defamatory facts as the 
basis for the opinion 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the evening times 
argued that the legal definition used by the state court violates 
freespeech rights 
only false statements of fact and not the reporting of 
someones stated opinion can be libelous they said 
the newspapers appeal was supported in a 
friendofthecourt brief sumbitted by five news media 
organizations the reporters committee for freedom of the press 
the national association of broadcasters the newsletter 
association the radiotelevision news directors association and 
the society of professional journalists 
they said the evening times had been punished for attempting 
to fairly and neutrally report both sides of a controversial local 
matter 
the case is new england newspapers inc vs healey 881939 
</TEXT>
