<TEXT>
three people convicted of trespassing for 
handing out antiabortion booklets to students outside a texas high 
school lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment let stand rulings that distribution 
of the prolife literature on school grounds was not protected 
by the constitutions freespeech guarantees 
john harris patricia murphy and charles reed were arrested 
outside friendswood high school in galveston county on jan 22 
1987 after refusing to leave 
a state jury convicted them of criminal trespass and a judge 
sentenced each to 90 days probation and 40 hours of community 
service 
the high school where more than 1000 students attend classes 
is fronted by a public road that has no adjacent sidewalk there is 
no access to students from the roadside because most arrive by car 
or bus and are dropped off on school grounds 
in the appeal acted on today the three convicted trespassers 
contended that their peaceful action before the start of classes 
should be constitutionally protected 
the vehicle unloading area and adjacent grounds in front of 
the school should be considered a limited public forum where 
distribution of literature is allowed the appeal argued 
under past freespeech rulings a limited public forum is an 
area opened for use by certain speakers or on certain occasions 
but a texas appeals court ruled that the friendswood high 
grounds are not any kind of public forum and the handing out of 
booklets there is not constitutionally protected the appeals court 
upheld the convictions 
the place is not an area which by tradition has been devoted 
to public assembly or debate by the general public there is no 
evidence that it had ever been opened by the school authorities as 
a place for public expressive activity the state court said 
it added a limited public forum cannot be created simply 
because members of the public are permitted to come and go at 
will 
the case is harris vs texas 882077 
