<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a 12 
million bonus in fees awarded to the lawyers for consumers who sued 
over allegedly defective transmissions in some general motors cars 
the justices without comment turned away arguments that 
federal law does not allow such fee bonuses when lawyers win cases 
in which there was a substantial risk of nonpayment because of a 
loss 
various lawsuits against gm each alleging that less efficient 
engines and transmissions were substituted in certain lines of 
cars were consolidated into one class action case in 1982 
the case was settled in 1985 after gm agreed to establish a 17 
million fund to be shared by those who sued 
a federal judge awarded the consumers lawyers nearly 2 million 
in fees to be paid out of the fund the award was based on time 
expended and reasonable hourly rates 
the judge refused to enhance the fee award as a bonus for taking 
a risky case on a contingency fee basis ruling that the federal 
magnusonmoss act bars any such risk multiplier of a lawyers 
fees 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals threw out the award ruling 
last year and ordered the judge to apply a risk multiplier in the 
gm case 
the judge then awarded an additional 12 million in lawyer fees 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for gm argued that the 
appeals court ruling conflicts with language in the magnusonmoss 
act and with a 1987 supreme court decision limiting lawyerfee 
bonuses 
the 7th circuit court rejected a narrow reading of the federal 
laws language the appeals court said the 1987 ruling did not 
apply to the gm case because a settlement had resulted in a common 
fund for payments to consumers and their lawyers 
gm lawyers called the appeals court ruling a patent evasion 
of the 1987 high court ruling they said the appeals court decision 
will increase the incentive for plaintiffs attorneys to clog the 
courts with marginal lawsuits in the hope of recovering large 
multipliers while spawning complex litigation over the collateral 
issue of attorneys fees 
gms appeal was supported in a friendofthecourt brief 
submitted by the national association of counties the national 
governors association the national league of cities and the us 
conference of mayors 
the brief noted that state and local governments are among the 
defendants most frequently sued under federal statutes providing 
for awards of attorney fees 
the case is gm vs skelton 881848 
</TEXT>
