<TEXT>
angolan rebel leader jonas savimbi is calling 
on the bush administration to take a more active diplomatic role to 
head off the possible collapse of peace talks designed to end the 
14year old civil war in his homeland 
savimbi said sunday he will carry that message to president 
bush other senior administration officials and congressional 
leaders this week he said a stronger us role is appropriate in 
light of the long history of us diplomatic activity in the area 
the united states knows the players said savimbi head of 
the unita rebel group 
bush will meet with savimbi on thursday to discuss current 
developments in southern africa including the national 
reconciliation process in angola and the proposals to end the 
fighting in that country white house spokesman marlin fitzwater 
said today 
angola seemed on the verge of a peace settlement in june when 
representatives of the leftist government and of savimbis 
usbacked rebel movement reached agreement on a ceasefire and on 
negotiations intended to lead to national reconciliation 
but the truce broke down in august with each side blaming the 
other and the situation has been aggravated during zairemediated 
talks by profound differences over what constitutes national 
reconciliation 
savimbi speaking with two american reporters on sunday 
reaffirmed his view that a settlement can come about only through 
the creation of a national unity government whose main task would 
be to arrange for free and fair elections 
the government of angola meanwhile has said reconciliation 
should consist mainly of the rebels integration into the existing 
political and military establishment 
savimbi also said he was prepared to meet with a highlevel 
angolan foreign ministry delegation which is due to arrive here on 
wednesday 
however in the talks mediated by zaire the two sides have 
refused to negotiate in the same room adding to savimbis 
frustration is the perception among some that zaire president 
mobutu sese seko has embraced the angolan governments view of the 
requirements for peace 
on sunday however savimbi declined to criticize mobutu 
concentrating his fire instead on the angolan government 
the soviet union has been angolas chief supplier of military 
equipment cuba has had troops in angola since 1975 but in december 
agreed to withdraw them by 1991 as part of a usmediated 
settlement the united states has been providing military and other 
assistance to unita since 1986 
savimbi said election processes are being used to bring about 
change in countries as diverse as poland and namibia where south 
african colonial rule is ending and he said elections are the only 
guarantee of peace in angola 
the power has to come from the people he said adding that 
he is confident the majority of angolans are on unitas side 
</TEXT>
