<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed pennsylvania 
to require its state judges to retire at age 70 
the court without comment turned away arguments that such a 
mandatory retirement age for judges is unconstitutional 
the controversy may have had special poignancy at the nations 
highest court where four of the nine justices are over 70 and a 
fifth will turn 70 next year 
justices william j brennan justice thurgood and harry a 
blackmun are over 80 justice byron r white is 72 and justice 
john paul stevens will turn 70 on april 20 each has life tenure 
as do all federal judges 
since 1968 the pennsylvania constitution has required all state 
judges who generally are elected to 10year terms to step down 
at 70 
four judges challenged the state constitutional provision 
saying it conflicts with the equalprotection and dueprocess 
guarantees offered in the federal constitution 
but the state supreme court last march 1 upheld the mandatory 
retirement scheme as a rational way to promote legitimate state 
purposes 
the state court identified those purposes as 
continually bringing in younger judges while retaining 
parttime services of retired judges willing and able to help out 
eliminating unpleasantness of removing aged and disabled judges 
on an individual selective basis 
preventing harm caused by senile judges 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the four state judges 
attacked each stated purpose 
removing older judges to make room for younger ones is unfair 
legally unsupportable and unwise the appeal argued the public 
interest is not served by forcing mature experienced judges off 
the bench before their elected terms expire 
it added that because chronological age bears no scientific 
relationship to mental competence a blanket policy on retirement 
denies judges their rights to individualized determinations of 
their fitness for service 
removing the unpleasantness that may accompany such individual 
determinations has never been considered a legitimate excuse for 
rank discrimination the appeal said 
the mandatory retirement is not an effective way of protecting 
the public from senile judges the appeal said because mental 
incompetence may set in far earlier than someones 70th birthday 
the justices in 1976 upheld a massachusetts law requiring 
mandatory retirement of state police officers at age 50 and in 
1979 upheld a federal law requiring mandatory retirement of foreign 
service officers at age 60 
the four state judges who appealed the pennsylvania mandatory 
retirement are leon katz robert wright john rauhauser jr and 
william pfadt 
the case is katz vs pennsylvania 8980 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

