<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to disturb a 
states ban on telephone solicitation for prearranged funerals 
the court without comment rejected arguments by an insurance 
firm and two funeral directors that such a virginia law violates 
their freespeech rights 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals last march upheld a 1951 
virginia law banning the telephoning of potential customers to line 
up funeral business 
the appeals court said the constitution permits such 
restrictions on commercial speech 
the law was challenged by guardian plans inc an 
insurancefunded funeral program and two funeral homes that 
participate in the plan 
guardian sells prearranged or preneed funerals by 
including in the companys life insurance policies benefits to pay 
for funerals when a policyholder dies the family must agree to 
release the policy proceeds to a funeral home 
guardian said the plan is intended to be humane and a help to 
customers sparing family members the anguish of deciding how much 
to pay for a funeral at the time of a loved ones death 
but the virginia board of funeral directors and embalmers 
saying it was trying to protect consumers complained about the 
soliciting of business over the phone 
guardian and its participating funeral homes said the state 
board is influenced by the funeral industry and that the ban on 
phone solicitations is a ploy to reduce competition 
the 4th circuit court said the virginia statute leaves open 
ample alternatives for guardian and its plan participants to 
advertise their services consequently virginias ban on 
telemarketing does not violate the first amendment 
guardians appeal was supported by the american cemetery 
association which represents 2000 funeral homes nationwide 
the associations lawyers cited a statement by federal trade 
commission officials that restricting such telephone solicitations 
is anticompetitive 
the case is guardian plans vs teague 8938 
</TEXT>
