<TEXT>
alaskas attempt to forestall offshore oil and 
gas exploration in its bristol bay suffered a supreme court setback 
today 
the court over one dissenting vote left intact rulings that 
allowed the federal government last year to sell leases on 56 
million acres of bristol bay off alaskas southwestern coast 
justice harry a blackmun voted to hear arguments in the case 
but four votes are needed to grant such review 
the court turned away warnings by alaska gov steve cowper and 
others that an oil spill in bristol bay could do more environmental 
harm than the massive exxon valdez spill in alaskas prince william 
sound last march 
the disputed leases were sold for nearly 100 million after a 
federal judge and the 9th us circuit court of appeals rejected a 
challenge by cowper and numerous enviromental groups fishing 
associations and alaska communities 
the federal government first began considering oil and gas 
leasing in the north aleutian basin which underlies bristol bay 
in 1974 
after twice canceling plans for lease sales in the bay at 
alaskas request the secretary of interior in 1982 proposed 
leasing all 325 million acres beginning in 1985 
the secretary in response to concerns expressed by alaska 
officials later restricted the leasing to the southwest corner of 
the region by deleting nearly 83 percent of the acreage from the 
sale 
under the federal outer continental shelf lands act the 
department of interior must give the governor of any affected state 
a chance to make recommendations about any proposed lease sale 
the governor recommended that the federal government delay 
selling any bristol bay leases for eight years and then not sell 
any tracts within 25 miles of shore the interior secretary 
rejected both recommendations sparking the lawsuit 
the appeal acted on today contended that the interior secretary 
violated the continental shelf law because his rejection of the 
states recommendations was arbitrary and capricious 
in the appeal alaska attorney general douglas baily referred to 
last marchs oil spill by the grounded tanker exxon valdez as a 
dramatic example of the devastating impact of oil on biological 
resources 
bristol bay and the north aleutian basin are substantially 
more remote and inaccessible than prince william sound the 
weather is much more problematic efforts to clean up an oil 
spill in this area accordingly would be even less successful than 
in the sound the appeal said 
it accused the federal government of not striking a proper 
balance between satisfying the nations thirst for oil and gas 
and protecting one of the most biologically productive and 
important areas in the world 
the appeal was supported by the attorneys general of california 
florida massachusetts new jersey north carolina oregon texas 
and washington and by the south carolina coastal council 
the bush administration urged the justices to reject the appeal 
justice department lawyers said federal law gives the interior 
secretary not a governor the authority to make a final decision 
on lease sales 
the case is cowper vs secretary of interior 882000 
</TEXT>
