the supreme court today refused to bar states 
from using abandoned property laws to recover some unclaimed 
insurance benefits 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by an insurance 
company ordered to turn over to connecticut 25 million in 
unclaimed benefits 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals ruled last february that 
the states power to collect the money is not preempted by the 
federal employee retirement income security act erisa which 
regulates pensions and other employee benefit programs 
aetna life insurance co which provides group health and 
accident coverage for workers said it should be allowed to keep 
unclaimed benefits and use the money to lower its premiums or 
increase benefits 
the insurance company said tens of millions of dollars could be 
at stake if all states sought to recover unclaimed benefits 
connecticut in 1981 amended its laws on abandoned property or 
escheating to enable the state to acquire property left unclaimed 
after three rather than seven years 
the state said aetna must turn over to it 25 million in 
unclaimed benefits 
a federal judge ruled in favor of aetna but the 2nd circuit 
court reversed that decision 
we think that the impact of connecticuts escheat law on erisa 
benefit plans is too tenuous remote and peripheral to require 
preemption of the state law by the federal statute the appeals 
court said 
the case is aetna vs borges 881883 
