<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed its decision 
barring prosecutors from excluding potential jurors based on their 
race to be applied to all noncriminal trials in three southern 
states 
the justices over one dissenting vote let stand a federal 
appeals court ruling in a georgia case that extended their 1986 
decision to all civil trials 
although todays action sets no national precedent it leaves 
intact a binding precedent for courts in georgia alabama and 
florida 
justice byron r white voted to hear arguments in the georgia 
case but four votes are needed to grant such review 
the justices in 1986 curtailed dramatically the traditionally 
broad power of prosecutors to bar prospective jurors from trials by 
using peremptory or automatic challenges 
the court ruled that the exclusion of potential jurors from any 
criminal trial because of their race violates the equalprotection 
rights of defendants and of those people excluded 
at the time of the ruling legal experts said it likely would 
not apply to peremptory challenges made by defense lawyers in 
criminal trials or to any civil or noncriminal trial 
but the 11th us circuit court of appeals last jan 17 took a 
much more expansive view of the supreme courts 1986 ruling 
the appeals court reinstated a lawsuit filed by a black man 
against the richmond county ga deputy sheriff who shot him the 
appeals court said the trial judge must determine whether the 
deputy sheriffs lawyer used two peremptory challenges to exclude 
black potential jurors for nonracial reasons 
we hold that the 1986 ruling applies in civil as well as 
criminal cases said the 11th circuit court which has 
jurisdiction over georgia alabama and florida 
some government action must be present for the 14th amendments 
guarantee of equal protection to be violated but the appeals court 
said such a violation can be found even in a lawsuit in which 
neither the government nor a government employee is involved 
when blacks are excluded from jury service on account of their 
race the trial judge constitutes the discriminatory state 
actor the appeals court said 
although the appeals court did not say so the decisions 
rationale would appear to mean that the prohibition against 
racebased juror exclusions applies to criminal defense lawyers as 
well 
in the georgia case deputy sheriff frank tiller shot willie 
albert fludd while attempting to apprehend a suspected narcotics 
trafficker fludd sued tiller in federal court under a muchused 
civil rights law 
the case is tiller vs fludd 882088 
</TEXT>
