<TEXT>
a former delta airlines pilot fired for 
operating a commercial jet while drunk lost a supreme court appeal 
today in his effort to win back his job 
the justices over one dissenting vote let stand lower court 
rulings that the pilots reinstatement would be contrary to public 
policy 
a labor arbitration board previously had ordered his 
reinstatement 
justice byron r white voted to hear arguments in the case but 
four votes are needed to grant such review 
william d day a bostonbased pilot for delta was fired in 
1985 after airline officials discovered he had been drunk while 
commanding a flight from bangor maine to boston 
the flight was without incident 
shortly after his firing day was medically diagnosed as an 
alcoholic after treatment he was recertified by the federal 
aviation administration 
day challenged his firing and under the terms of a contract 
delta and his union the air line pilots association his grievance 
was submitted to a fivemember arbitration board 
comprised of two members appointed by the airline two appointed 
by the union and one neutral chairman the board split 32 in 
finding that day had been fired without just cause 
although stating that day was guilty of serious misconduct the 
board concluded that he should have been offered the option of 
enrolling in deltas alcohol rehabilitation program the board 
ordered his reinstatement without back pay 
delta challenged the boards reinstatement order in federal 
court and us district judge orinda evans in atlanta overturned 
the board 
requiring delta to cooperate with day and the faa in 
recertifying day is violative of public policy the judge ruled 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals upheld that ruling last 
dec 8 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the air line pilots 
association argued that the lower court rulings conflict with a 
1987 supreme court decision that limited the power of federal 
judges to overrule labor arbitrators 
in that decision the court ruled unanimously that judges may 
reverse an arbitration award for publicpolicy reasons only if the 
award creates an explicit conflict with laws or legal precedent 
such judicial reversals cannot be based on general 
considerations f supposed public interest the justices said in 
their 1987 ruling 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the pilots union 
called the lower court rulings examples of the continuing erosion 
of the doctrine of finality of arbitration awards 
they urged the justices to restore the arbitration board ruling 
that would reinstate day 
the case is alpa vs delta 881901 
</TEXT>
