<TEXT>
about 25000 blacks demanded 
clemency for two condemned african national congress guerrillas 
today in the largest protest march ever held in one of south 
africas nominally independent tribal homelands 
the marchers most of them schoolchildren paraded peacefully 
through the center of umtata capital of transkei 
some carried african national congress flags and displayed 
placards urging the release of two members of the guerrilla 
movement who are on death row in transkei for a 1986 bombing which 
killed two people at the wild coast sun a posh gambling resort 
overlooking the indian ocean 
the homelands official radio estimated the crowd at 25000 and 
said police did not interfere 
the protest came a day after transkeis military leader maj 
gen bantu holomisa declared at a funeral service that he would 
consider holding a referendum to let homeland voters decide if they 
wanted to rejoin south africa 
the star south africas largest daily newspaper said the 
government faced a major challenge to its grand apartheid plan 
if holomisa proceeded with a referendum the result said the star 
would be an overwhelming vote to rejoin south africa thus 
repudiating the white governments longstanding contention that 
blacks preferred autonomy in separate ethnic states 
the homeland system also came under heavy criticism sunday in 
botshabelo a vast rural shantytown in the orange free state which 
the government has placed under the jurisdiction of qwaqwa one of 
six semiautonomous homelands an estimated 15000 to 20000 of 
botshabelos 500000 residents marched in protest against their 
incorporation into qwaqwa which is 180 miles from their community 
many botshabelo residents fear qwaqwa may be declared 
independent thus depriving them of south african citizenship like 
many other blacks they feel south africa despite its segregation 
laws offers better opportunities than the impoverished homelands 
in regard to pensions employment and housing 
south africas 28 million blacks have voting rights only in the 
homelands and in local elections national policy is controlled by 
the 5 million whites 
holomisa at the funeral sunday of a tribal chief who opposed 
transkeis independence shared a podium for the first time with 
prominent antiapartheid activists speakers at the service 
denounced the homeland system and praised the late chief sabata 
dalindyebo for his staunch opposition to the excision of transkei 
from south africa in 1976 
transkei was the first of four homelands to accept 
independence from south africa as part of a plan by white 
officials to create separate nations for each major black tribe 
none of the four are recognized internationally 
south africas foreign minister pik botha declined to comment 
on holomisas statement saying he had received no official 
communication from transkei a ministry official requesting 
anonymity said any bid by transkei to renounce its independence 
would be a matter for negotiations between south africa and the 
homeland 
holomisa 34 took power in transkei in a bloodless coup in 
1987 he is the first leader of a nominally independent homeland to 
make favorable references to the african national congress and he 
reportedly held secret talks earlier this year with the groups 
exiled president oliver tambo 
transkei lies along south africas southern coast between the 
port cities of durban and east london it covers about 18000 
square miles and has about 35 million residents 
</TEXT>
