<DOCNO> AP891002-0156 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken monday by the supreme court 
 
sobriety checkpoints 
 
the court agreed to decide whether police nationwide may try to 
curb drunken driving by stopping motorists at sobriety checkpoints 
the justices said they will review michigan court rulings that 
struck down that states sobriety checkpoint program as an 
unconstitutional invasion of privacy 
courts in other states have upheld virtually identical 
checkpoint programs 
the case is michigan department of state police vs sitz 
881897 
 
patronage 
 
the court agreed to decide whether public employers may be 
forced to put aside partisanship when hiring promoting and 
transferring workers 
the court said it will hear an appeal by two men and a woman who 
said their job status suffered because they didnt support the 
republican party in illinois 
the cases are rutan vs illinois republican party 881872 and 
frech vs rutan 882074 
 
worker safety 
 
the court let states file criminal charges against employers 
accused of neglecting the health and safety of workers 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling in an illinois 
case that federal workplace regulations do not bar such state 
prosecutions 
the case is asta vs illinois 881783 
 
bail 
 
the court agreed to consider increasing the federal governments 
power to keep some accused criminals behind bars while they await 
trial 
the court said it will review a ruling in a new mexico case that 
forces the government to free on bail some defendants deemed to 
be dangerous or a risk to flee before trial 
the case is us vs montalvomurillo 89163 
 
trespassing 
 
the court turned aside an appeal by three people convicted of 
trespassing for handing out antiabortion booklets to students 
outside a texas high school 
the court without comment let stand rulings that distribution 
of the prolife literature on school grounds was not protected 
by the constitutions freespeech guarantees 
the case is harris vs texas 882077 
 
evangelical group 
 
the court turned aside an appeal by an evangelical christian 
group ordered to return most of the 65 million donated by a 
wealthy exmember 
the court without comment let stand rulings that the group 
the bible speaks received the donations after exerting undue 
influence on department store heiress elizabeth dayton dovydenas 
the religious group now must return 55 million 
the case is the bible speaks vs dovydenas 881977 
 
foster care 
 
the court refused to revive an allegedly abused foster childs 
federal lawsuit against the social workers and government agency 
that placed him in his foster home 
the justices without comment let stand a federal appeals court 
ruling in a maryland case that no such right to sue exists 
the case is milburn vs anne arundel county department of social 
services 8996 
 
mafia appeals 
 
the court turned aside appeals by eight mafia figures from new 
york city convicted in the 1979 killings of crime chieftain carmine 
galante and two of his associates 
the court without comment let stand the federal racketeering 
convictions of family bosses anthony salerno anthony corallo and 
carmine persico highranking mobsters salvatore santoro 
christopher furnari and gennaro langella and mob members anthony 
indelicato and ralph scopo 
the cases are indelicato vs us 881881 salerno vs us 
882060 persico vs us 882061 scopo vs us 882071 
 
lawyers fees 
 
the court agreed to decide whether lawyers who win civil rights 
cases can collect a big chunk of their clients awards under an 
agreement made when the attorneys were hired 
the court said it will hear an appeal by a california man 
awarded 212 million and then ordered to pay 40 percent of the 
judgment to his lawyer 
the case is venegas vs mitchell 881725 
 
pilot 
 
the court turned down the appeal of a former delta airlines 
pilot fired for operating a commercial jet while drunk who is 
trying to win back his job 
the justices over one dissenting vote let stand lower court 
rulings that the pilots reinstatement would be contrary to public 
policy 
the case is alpa vs delta 881901 
 
automobile insurance 
 
the court let states require automobile insurance for motorists 
who say it violates their religious convictions 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by a south dakota 
man who believes having insurance belittles a promise from god to 
provide in any situation 
the case acted is cosgrove vs south dakota 8910 
 
general motors suit 
 
the court let stand a 12 million bonus in fees awarded to the 
lawyers of consumers who sued over allegedly defective 
transmissions in some general motor cars 
the justices without comment turned away arguments that 
federal law does not allow such fee bonuses when lawyers win cases 
in which there was a substantial risk of nonpayment because of a 
loss 
the case is gm vs skelton 881848 
 
bankruptcy 
 
the court said it will consider placing new limits on the 
ability of convicted criminals to avoid making restitution to their 
victims by declaring bankruptcy 
the court agreed to hear an appeal by pennsylvania officials 
seeking to recover 4145 from a couple who pleaded guilty to 
welfare fraud 
the case is pennsylvania vs davenport 89156 
 
hustler 
 
the court rejected an appeal by an antipornography activist who 
says sexually explicit photographs and caricatures in hustler 
magazine libeled her and invaded her privacy 
the court without comment refused to revive a 150 million 
lawsuit by feminist author andrea dworkin 
the case is dworkin vs hustler 881900 
 
grand jury witnesses 
 
the court agreed to decide whether states may prohibit grand 
jury witnesses from making public their own testimony once the 
investigation has ended 
the justices said they will review an attempt by florida 
officials to block a former newspaper reporter from disclosing 
details of his appearance before a grand jury three years ago 
a federal appeals court said a state law barring such public 
disclosure violates freespeech rights 
the case is butterworth vs smith 881993 
 
medicaid 
 
the court agreed to decide whether hospitals and nursing care 
homes may sue in federal court to challenge how a staterun 
medicaid program reimburses their costs 
the court said it will review a ruling that would allow a 
hospital association to invoke a federal civil rights law in suing 
virginia over the states medicaid reimbursement rates 
the case is baliles vs virginia hospital association 882043 
 
disability 
 
the court agreed to consider making it easier for the government 
to cut off disability pay to some former federal workers 
the court said it will review a ruling that barred termination 
of a disability annuity for a california man who was given 
incorrect information about benefits eligibility 
the case is office of personnel mangement vs richmond 881943 
 
black lung 
 
the supreme court agreed to decide whether a federal law 
unfairly makes it too difficult for coal miners who contract 
black lung disease to obtain a lawyers help when seeking 
benefits 
the justices said they will review a west virginia supreme court 
of appeals ruling that the system for awarding lawyer fees in black 
lung benefits cases violates dueprocess rights 
the case is labor department vs triplett 881671 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

