<TEXT>
thousands of wouldbe emigrants lined up outside 
the us embassy for visa applications monday as new rules on 
emigration took effect but the embassy quickly ran out of new 
forms and turned away thouands of angry people 
consular officials distributed 30500 applications at a rate of 
100 per minute with a maximum of five allotted each person before 
running out in about 2 hours 
another 70000 application forms were expected to be delivered 
to the embassy by the end of the week an official said and 
300000 more shortly thereafter we hope to be out of the woods 
by friday said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
many soviets were angry at being turned away and are upset at 
the new regulations which require applicants to deal with 
washington rather than the embassy in moscow the changes were made 
because the moscow embassy was unable to handle the flood of 
applications 
it is a conspiracy between the us congress and soviet 
authorities said one woman who refused to give her name 
the united states embassy should be ashamed of the way they 
are treating us said another soviet who also refused to 
identify himself 
the united states has long urged the soviet union to liberalize 
its emigration policy but now that soviet rules have become more 
lax the united states has found it cannot accept all the soviets 
who wish to emigrate 
the new regulations that went into effect oct 1 spurred a surge 
in the number of people lining up at the embassy and more than 
15000 lined up over the weekend to be among the first to get new 
forms 
they organized themselves into groups of 100 with group leaders 
holding up signs so people could secure a place in line then leave 
and return later 
on monday morning traffic around the embassy on moscows busy 
garden ring road was snarled and the sidewalks around the embassy 
were jammed with people 
when the applications ran out people still were lined up 
between signs with numbers up to 11000 according to soviets at a 
shack set up to register for a place in line 17000 people had 
signed up over the weekend 
a reporter visiting the embassy was besieged by hundreds of 
people who though he was a consular official they demanded to know 
when they would get the applications and whether photocopies would 
be acceptable in washington 
several times during the day embassy officials waded into the 
crowd that had waited overnight to explain that new forms would be 
available wednesday and that photocopies would be acceptable 
hundreds of people have lined up outside the embassy every 
working day since soviet officials began liberalizing emigration 
policies last year and us officials have been swamped with 
paperwork 
under the new regulations applications will be sent directly to 
washington rather than evaluated by moscow consular officials 
an official said last week that the embassy is likely to receive 
300000 applications in the next year but will be able to accept 
only about 7000080000 
following ceilings set in washington the united states will 
accept 50000 soviets classified as refugees and another 
2000030000 on a socalled parole system that does not guarantee 
any government support 
the new system also gives priority to people with close 
relatives already in the united states and to those who belong to 
groups that the united states considers to be persecuted in the 
soviet union 
