gorbachev urged legislators to discuss the strike ban overnight 
and be ready to vote on it tuesday 
he referred to the possible ban on strikes as a necessary 
measure which are called for to protect democratization from 
anarchy and irresponsible management 
plans for future economic development are under threat 
because of the strikes he said 
emergency measures to bolster the rapidly faltering economy 
overshadowed premier nikolai i ryzhkovs lengthy presentation of a 
package of legislation covering the governments longterm 
proposals on property ownership and use of land and taxes 
voronin told the legislature the soviet economy had lost 615 
billion in july and august alone due to strikes and that supplies 
of fuel are low enough that the country might be unable to supply 
enough heat to see soviet citizens through the winter 
the most damaging of a series of strikes to hit the soviet union 
this year was a walkout in july by thousands of coal miners in the 
far north siberia and the don basin of the eastern ukraine 
that strike alone cost the country millions of rubles and the 
government agreed to a package of economic and social improvements 
that officials say will cost about 3 billion 
strikes also have become a way of expressing ethnic discontent 
such actions have idled the nagornokarabakh region the center of 
a dispute between the neighboring caucasus republics of armenia and 
azerbaijan 
