victims or families of victims of foreign 
governmentsponsored torture could sue for damages in us district 
courts under a bill passed monday by the house 
approved on a 3624 vote the legislation extends to us 
citizens who have been tortured abroad the same civil redress now 
available to foreign nationals tortured in the united states 
this bill puts torturers on notice they will find no safe 
haven in the united states said rep bruce morrison dconn 
all of the four votes against the bill were cast by republicans 
reps joe barton of texas robert k dornan of california jon l 
kyl and bob stump both of arizona 
rep jack brooks dtexas chairman of the house judiciary 
committee said the legislation was prompted in part because of a 
ruling in 1985 by thenus circuit court of appeals judge robert 
bork 
in a case involving alleged terrorist acts by the palestine 
liberation organization bork ruled that courts could hear such 
suits having a possible impact on us foreign relations only 
through an explicit grant from congress 
the bill deals only with officially condoned acts of torture or 
extrajudicial killings and does not touch upon acts of torture or 
killings by private groups 
