<TEXT>
the sony walkman the dictaphone and the 
braun coffeemaker were successful industrial designs that are the 
focus of designers gathered to look for an edge on products of the 
future 
those products succeeded because their companies took their 
industrial designers seriously said earl powell director of the 
design management institute of boston which is conducting a 
fourday symposium with the harvard business school 
most business managers say they use engineers or others to 
create a product and then get the flakes to get the color picked 
out powell said 
powell one of those flakes by training said designers can 
be the consumers advocate inside the firm choosing the right size 
knobs and switches that can make a product work easily or not 
yamaha corp which had an electronic saxaphone in the exhibit 
used its designers to find a modern shape that would match the new 
technology of digital wind music 
the first design was described by one yamaha worker as a snake 
that ate a lunch box several versions later the final product 
resembles a futuristic rifle embellished with the standard finger 
pads in black the instrument is a long black tube bent down at 
one end for the mouthpiece 
the sound that emerges from the instrument can range from 
synthesized voices to the acoustic timbres of wind instruments the 
product dominates the professional wind digital music market 
according to yamaha 
designers at ab bahco vertyg the tools division of the 
investment ab bahco of sweden helped the company maintain its 
share in the screwdriver market while increasing its profit margin 
by 20 percent said powell 
the company had discovered in market research that carpenters 
use a twohanded grip 70 percent of the time and gave the problem 
to its designers 
the new screwdriver which was presented at the exhibit is 
shaped like the numeral 8 with textured polypropylene where the 
handle widens 
at braun business managers faced the problem of an extremely 
low share of the coffeemaker market the kf20 model introduced in 
1972 had won awards for its simple cylindrical design but it was 
too expensive 
artists and designers would collect our things to add to their 
collections but we were not succesful said dieter rems the 
companys chief designer who spoke at the symposium monday 
the solution which included cheaper materials and fewer parts 
may not seem that innovative at first glance but rems said the new 
design marketed as the kf40 used one heater for both coffee and 
water instead of two which cut the price dramatically 
more than 25 million units of the new design sold in 1988 
giving braun a 12 percent market share the company makes 12000 
units a day 
rems said having the designers talk to the manufacturers was a 
crucial element in the braun story because the design could be 
adapted to cut production costs 
powell said he thinks if american businesses adopted more of 
these tactics the competitiveness of us products would improve 
vastly 
