<TEXT>
the house on monday overwhelmingly approved 
president bushs compromise plan to extend steel import 
restrictions on 29 foreign trading partners until april 1992 
the vote was 35410 
bushs plan announced july 25 called for immediate 
negotiations with japan south korea and other leading 
steelexporting nations to extend annual limitations on the volume 
of steel allowed to be shipped to the united states 
the original pacts which expired saturday were negotiated by 
the reagan administration in 1984 to give domestic steelmakers 
breathing space from subsidized foreign competition 
many steeldistrict lawmakers had pushed the administration this 
summer to extend the curbs for five years but bush opted for a 
smallerscale 2year program in deference to steelusing 
manufacturers who argued that the quotas have driven up steel 
prices and caused supply shortages of some steel products 
the compromise all but eliminated debate on the house floor 
opposition came largely from freetraders who felt the steel 
industry has had enough protection 
its not my first choice said rep bill frenzel rminn 
who had opposed the industrys requests for a longer extension 
nevertheless i have to admit its about as good a compromise as 
could be achieved 
rep joseph gaydos dpa who represents a western pennsylvania 
steel district said the reagan and bush program is not a 
cureall but has been the most effective method of dealing with 
dumped imports 
this legislation is basically and fundamentally giving the 
steel industry in this country a little more time to become 
competitive and theyre well underway gaydos said 
sen bob packwood rore has introduced a companion measure in 
the senate but no action on it has yet been taken 
with the old steel program due to expire sept 30 the bush 
administration could not afford to wait until congress acted to 
begin the painstaking process of negotiating new import ceilings 
trade representatives from japan south korea the european 
community mexico venezuela and romania were all in town last week 
for meetings on renewing their pacts 
many of the negotiations are already complete according to us 
trade representative carla hills even though congress has not yet 
finished work on the bill she said steel imports would continued 
to be monitored by the department of commerce and the us customs 
service 
no details on individual pacts have yet been announced 
</TEXT>
