it was once called the american clyde after 
the clyde river in scotland then a major shipbuilding center in 
europe now the delaware river is losing the last of its onceproud 
shipbuilding yards partially because of a general slump in the 
industry brought on by new government policies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when the unfinished hulls of two navy ships 
leave the yard of pennsylvania shipbuilding co the delaware river 
will be without a shipbuilding business for the first time in more 
than 300 years 
since william west built the amity in 1682 the year william 
penn came from england companies putting together seagoing ships 
have been a part of the delaware river landscape at one time or 
another there were 38 shipyards along the river and its 
tributaries 
it has been in decline here for decades but spokesmen say a 
national slump in shipbuilding aggravated by new government 
policies really finished off a onceproud industry that was a 
national leader 
for example john fitch advertised steamboat trips along the 
delaware river 17 years before robert fulton ran his clermont along 
the hudson some of the civil warera ironclad monitors were 
built here 
delaware valley shipyards built boats to defend the americas 
cup in wilmington del the pusey amp jones shipyard built them for 
trade on the amazon river 
in 1915 with war under way in europe american international 
shipbuilding corp built what was then the worlds largest shipyard 
50 shipways employing 34000 workers it turned out 122 cargo 
ships and troop transports in two years 
the river was nicknamed the american clyde after the clyde 
in scotland then the center of european iron shipbuilding 
the proud tradition continued down to 1960 when the huge 
aircraft carrier kitty hawk was launched from the new york 
shipbuilding corp yard in camden nj right across the river 
from the philadelphia waterfront that yard closed soon after and 
is now being demolished 
the kitty hawk is being modernized now in philadelphia at the 
us navy yard which does ship repair work but hasnt built a ship 
from the keel up since 1971 
the two ships the navy ordered from pennsylvania shipbuilding 
sit at the rivers edge one tied up in a slip and the other braced 
in a dry dock and minus the bow stern and deckhouse a mortgage 
agreement filed in the delaware county recorder of deeds office 
gives the navy title to four parcels of land owned by penn ship if 
the company fails to pay for the costs of finding another company 
to finish the work 
pennsylvania shipbuilding was known as sun shipbuilding amp 
