<TEXT>
the last working commercial shipyard in 
pennsylvania was started by an oil executive making sure his 
company had enough tankers it went out of business trying to 
finish a pair of military fuel ships 
sun oil co incorporated sun shipbuilding amp drydock co in 1916 
a year after company president j howard pew had taken a business 
trip to germany and been impressed with that countrys naval 
strength 
sun ships first vessel the ss chester sun slid down the ways 
in october 1917 by the end of world war i the yard had built six 
tankers plus three minesweepers for the navy 
over the years sun ship emerged as one of the nations largest 
privately owned shipyards its sun doxford diesel engine eventually 
made it the biggest american manufacturer of large marine diesel 
it also launched the first allwelded tanker the ss white flash 
in 1931 
but its glory years were during world war ii when an average of 
a ship a week rolled down its 28 ways on one day the yard 
launched three ships 
by the end of the war sun ship had produced more than 250 ships 
40 percent of all us tankers built it converted armed and 
repaired 1000 more the yard employed 33500 people 
but the end of the war brought a sharp decline in ship 
construction the other yards on the delaware river began closing 
and by 1975 only sun ship was left by the end of 1980 the parent 
sun co estimated it had lost more than 200 million keeping the 
shipyard alive 
sun announced it was getting out of the shipbuilding business in 
january 1981 a company official estimated the shipyard would be 
sold for 30 million to 40 million 
in february 1982 the yard and its assets were sold for a 
reported 8 million to levingston industries inc a texas company 
that renamed the yard pennsylvania shipbuilding levingston sold 
control two years later to three real estate developers from 
mobile ala 
but shipbuilding hasnt been very successful for penn ship in 
may 1985 when the navy awarded the contract for two 677foot 
fleet oilers it was hailed as a deal that would keep the yard 
alive 
