<TEXT>
lifesaving drugs are often available in france 
long before they are on the market in the united states the reason 
is a difference in the bureaucracies of the two countries while 
some argue that the us food and drug administration should speed 
up its drug approval process others warn that its risky to be 
hasty 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in 1985 a desperately ill rock hudson was one of 
many aids patients who fled to france for a drug they couldnt get 
in the united states 
the drug didnt work but at the time it was the only hope and 
american doctors couldnt prescribe it 
last year french doctors began prescribing the socalled 
abortion pill to terminate pregnancies american women may not get 
it for years 
these are two examples among many in which the french became the 
first to receive the potential benefits of new drugs 
it happens because the french drug approval system is simpler 
and faster than that of the us food and drug administration 
advocates of the french system say it has elements that could be 
adopted in the united states cutting the time that americans must 
wait for new drugs 
the issue has become increasingly important as the fda faces 
growing pressure to speed the approval of experimental cancer and 
aids drugs that might help patients who would otherwise be unlikely 
to survive 
the fda has in fact responded to that pressure by speeding the 
approval of the aids drug azt and on sept 28 it announced that 
it was making a newer aids drug called ddi widely available while 
tests of its safety and effectiveness are still continuing 
defenders of the fda argue the french system has certain 
drawbacks that would make it unworkable in the united states 
the french system is faster because its very different 
says jerome halperin former deputy director of drugs at the fda 
in the united states the drug approval process is subject to 
enormous oversight by congress and consumer groups says halperin 
who is now with the us pharmacopeial convention a private 
organization that sets standards for drug quality purity and 
strength 
some public interest groups are calling for a speedup in drug 
approval halperin notes at the same time that others are arguing 
that the agency takes unnecessary risks by sometimes being too 
hasty 
the classic example of a drug being approved too quickly is 
thalidomide which caused severe birth defects after it was 
approved in europe in the late 1950s and early 1960s the drug was 
never approved in the united states 
oversight from congress and the public interest groups 
inevitably puts pressure on reviewers and slows down the 
drugapproval process halperin says similar government and public 
oversight does not exist in france 
there is hardly ever anybody from the ap or the new york times 
looking over their shoulders says dr michael weintraub a 
clinical pharmacologist at the university of rochester school of 
medicine in rochester ny who spent the 198081 academic year in 
france studying its pharmaceutical approval process our system 
is much more political 
most americans see that public scrutiny as important even 
though it might slow new drug approvals halperin says 
nevertheless he says there are examples of drugs that get 
approved here before they get approved in other countries 
including some aids drugs 
i think the fda has gone remarkably far in making experimental 
aids drugs available with as little administrative encumbrance as 
possible halperin says 
the principal difference between the french and american systems 
is that while the fda relies on an inhouse staff of drug 
reviewers the french rely on an outside committee of expert 
volunteers says dr yves juillet director of scientific affairs 
for the french national pharmaceutical industry association 
some of the volunteers are drawn from the drug industry itself 
that works well in france juillet says but the use of drug 
company scientists to review drugs in the united states would 
likely draw allegations of conflict of interest 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0264 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the french expert committee meets every other friday morning to 
review pending new drug applications individual committee members 
present written technical reviews of each application and then the 
committee makes its decisions 
in cases in which unusual speed is needed or in which research 
results are especially complicated the health ministry simply 
invites additional experts to join the committee for a time 
it doesnt cost a lot because people are not paid for that 
juillet said in an interview at broussais hospital in paris where 
he practices medicine 
a decision is generally rendered within a few months after a 
company sends in its research reports the health minister 
rubberstamps it 
when i was there the limit was four months and i almost 
never saw anything over four months weintraub says 
in contrast at the fda some drugs are quicker than others but 
by and large its about 18 months for approval after a final 
application has been submitted weintraub says 
in the french system everything is reviewed within an hour or 
an hourandahalf in one day at one presentation weintraub says 
the fda also places great emphasis on certain studies considered 
pivotal in demonstrating the safety and effectiveness of new drugs 
the most important thing the fda could learn from the french would 
be not focusing on the socalled pivotal studies but looking at 
all the studies and all the data weintraub says 
one of the drawbacks of the french system according to 
weintraub is that the health ministry does little until research 
is complete and the company is ready to ask for approval 
the fda requires a review of laboratory findings before it will 
allow a new drug to be tested on humans the french dont drug 
companies simply inform the health ministry that human trials are 
about to begin and the ministry rarely intervenes 
they cant guide you weintraub says the fda meets 
regularly with drug companies testing new drugs to advise the 
companies on what further research is needed for approval 
in france there are no contacts between the committee and the 
companies until the file is through juillet says 
when the file of research data is complete juillet acting as 
the industry representative makes the companys case before the 
committee my mission is to be a witness and defend the companies 
and give them information if there is a problem he says 
french drug companies have a much closer relationship with the 
health ministry than american companies do with the fda weintraub 
says because the reviewers dont work for the government its 
not a themandus thing 
in contrast fda reviewers and drug companies often deeply 
distrust each other company officials charge the fda with dragging 
its feet while the fda often blames delays on the inadequacy of 
the companies research 
juillet suggests the fda should rely more on outside reviewers 
i think the open system is a good thing working with people on 
the outside he says 
dr charles leighton a senior vicepresident at merck sharpe amp 
dohme research laboratories in blue bell pa says one reason 
french drug approvals are often faster is that the french have 
decided that the benefits of speeding new drug approval outweigh 
the risks 
they realize there might be a risk he says if youre the 
first country to approve a drug you might be the first to see a 
problem 
weintraub says history shows however that the french have not 
in fact been subject to more problems with drug sideeffects than 
have americans we arent saved from every problem drug nor are 
they exposed to every problem drug he says 
although he believes the fda has much to learn from the french 
weintraub praises the expertise of the fdas reviewers everybody 
respects those people theyre smart hardworking a lot of 
countries will allow marketing of the drug once the fda does 
we are the benchmark for good or ill 
</TEXT>
