<TEXT>
the startling boom of heavy artillery 
reverberates through the worlds highest mountains where for five 
years india and pakistan have been fighting for control of an icy 
wasteland while neither side will say how many casualities they 
have suffered they estimate only one in three resulted from combat 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the top of the world is the 
battleground in a largely unknown and undeclared war raging between 
india and pakistan a war in which wind snow and ice often take a 
greater toll than the enemy 
at stake is national prestige and possession of the siachen a 
himalayan wasteland wedged between pakistanoccupied kashmir and 
territory controlled by china 
after more than five years of fighting and artillery duels over 
what would appear to be a minor issue india and pakistan are 
trying to end the costly war 
prime minister rajiv gandhi of india and pakistani prime 
minister benazir bhutto confident they can do business are 
pushing to bury ancient animosities and move their countries into a 
friendlier era 
but while they talk of peace huge artillery guns continue to 
boom each startling blast echoing through the stillness of the 
cathedrallike mountains 
fifteen years ago few thought it possible to fight let alone 
hold ground for years in the higher reaches of the karakoram 
mountain range where lie the siachen and more than half of the 
worlds 20 tallest peaks 
never had battles been fought for any length of time at heights 
of up to 4 miles breathing air that contains less than half the 
oxygen at sea level and at temperatures that frequently drop to 50 
degrees below zero 
climb a 21000foot mountain anywhere else in the world and 
you get an award brig gen vr raghavan commander of the 
indian troops told foreign journalists flown to the base camp at 
the mouth of the siachen and then taken by helicopter up the 
45milelong 6milewide glacier 
the number of casualties on both sides remains a military 
secret although raghavan estimated only onethird are actually due 
to combat 
there are natural limits to this conflict the weather and 
the terrain he said here one has to fight constantly and even 
more doggedly to survive so much depends on so few and death can 
be just one false move away 
the conflicts roots can be traced to the 1947 partition of 
moslem pakistan and india which is predominantly hindu 
both countries have coveted the 85000 square miles of 
jammukashmir a predominantly moslem state that acceded to india 
the dispute led pakistan to grab about onethird of the 
territory in 1949 the two countries signed an agreement that drew 
a ceasefire line that stopped at the southern foot of the saltoro 
range running along the glaciers western edge toward the chinese 
border 
negotiators did not extend the line because there was no 
fighting in the region and glaciers were difficult to demarcate 
although there were minor adjustments following the 1965 and 1971 
indiapakistan wars the question of siachen was left unresolved 
almost from the beginning india has said it is entitled to 
control all of kashmir pakistan however says it has controlled 
the siachen all along citing mountaineering expeditions that for 
years sought its permission to enter and atlases published in the 
united states and britain in the early 1980s that showed the area 
under its control 
india first deployed troops to the siachen in april 1984 a move 
it said was merely to preempt a planned pakistani strike 
islamabad denied the charge 
the conflict slowly escalated with each side deploying 
thousands of soldiers erecting outposts and setting up bigger 
more powerful artillery 
in the winter of 1987 indian troops abandoned a 20000foot 
outpost on bilaford one of three key passes when they returned in 
the spring and found the pakistanis had moved in a fierce sixday 
battle ensued with both sides pounding the other with artillery 
pakistan retaliated three months later with its biggest strike 
of the war capturing one post and closing in on a second before 
the indians unleashed an artillery barrage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the secret to this conflict is to control the high ground and 
we do pakistan is on the lower slopes and we can punish them 
whenever necessary raghavan said as 130mm artillery guns fired 
reverberating through the canyons 
we have just given them our reply for firing at one of our 
posts 
indian soldiers posted on the peaks and ridges keep watch day 
and night for the other sides supply and patrols columns 
it is a lonely existence for the soldiers most of whom come 
from the palmfringed beaches of southern kerala state or the 
