<TEXT>
taipei taiwan forty years after generalissimo chiang kaishek 
and his nationalist chinese arrived in defeat from the mainland 
taiwan is prosperous the worlds 13th largest trading nation 
and democracy is beginning to take hold 
but in 1949 with mao tsetung communists in control of 
mainland china the outlook for the chinese nationalists on taiwan 
was bleak 
not only had they been routed from their homeland they faced a 
restive taiwanese population that viewed chiang and his 2 million 
or so followers as an occupying force 
the nationalists prevailed nevertheless by dint of 
authoritarian rule and clinging to their contention supported by 
the united states and other western nations that they were the 
legitimate rulers of china 
in the years since firmly guided economic policies have 
transformed taiwan into the economic success it is now as the 
island approaches its national day oct 10 double ten for the 
tenth day of the tenth month 
with prosperity at its peak and people demanding greater 
freedoms the nationalists have begun to loosen their authoritarian 
grip slowly bringing democracy to the island of 20 million and 
permitting contacts with the rival communist chinese for the first 
time since the civil war on the mainland 
many people used to be disappointed with the government and 
tried to emigrate whenever they had the chance said lu yali 
political science professor of national taiwan university they 
now feel there is some hope and have begun to care and criticize 
an agrarian economy based on rice and sugar production has given 
way to the manufacturing of textiles electronic products and 
machinery 
the formula was capitalism mixed with government policies 
designed to stimulate selected industries while the nationalists 
controlled major monopolies many of the lightindustry factories 
were familyrun operations that helped spread the wealth around the 
island 
annual per capita income rose from 50 in 1949 to 5512 last 
year gross national product soared from 12 billion 40 years ago 
to 119 billion in 1988 
exports led the way with foreign trade jumping from 300 
million in 1952 to 110 billion last year so much foreign exchange 
has poured in that the islands coffers bulge with 74 billion in 
reserves 
prosperity is everywhere on the streets of taipei porsche and 
bmw automobiles snake through the congested streets fancy 
restaurants are on almost every block and the latest electronic 
gadgets fill store windows 
indeed taipei the islands capital seems to lack nothing 
except foreign embassies 
while the island advanced on economic successes it faced bitter 
diplomatic defeats as the world recognized the communist chinese 
government in beijing 
only 24 countries mostly tiny island nations and latin american 
countries still recognize taiwan diplomatically down from 50 in 
1949 the communist chinese government has formal ties with 135 
countries 
the toughest blow came in 1978 when taiwans major ally the 
united states announced it was cutting diplomatic links and 
setting up formal relations with beijing 
the united states dismantled its military bases on taiwan and 
said military aid would not increase in quantity or quality 
but the us market did not close to taiwan and that helped 
assure its economic health 
chiang pengchien a leading opposition politician blamed 
taiwans diplomatic isolation on the dream of a reunified china 
ruled by a nationalist government 
the nationalists also used that dream in their efforts to 
justify their monopoly on political power and the harsh quelling of 
dissent 
the nationalists placed taiwan under martial law and refused to 
allow rival political parties or an opposition press critics who 
traveled overseas often were not allowed back many of those who 
stayed in taiwan were thrown in jail 
by claiming to be the rightful ruler of all china the 
nationalists insisted that native taiwanese who comprise about 80 
percent of the population could not replace any of the members of 
the legislature and electoral college who had been elected in 
mainland china before the civil war defeat 
but as the taiwanese prospered economically they demanded more 
political rights it was chiang kaisheks son the late president 
chiang chingkuo who finally launched the political liberalization 
the nationalists needed if they were to maintain popular support 
in 1987 chiang chingkuo lifted martial law which paved the 
way for the formation of opposition political parties some media 
restrictions were erased leading to a more critical press taiwan 
residents were allowed to visit relatives on the chinese mainland 
bringing a more relaxed attitude toward the communists 
</TEXT>
