<DOCNO> AP891002-0273 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
demonstrations became an almost daily occurrence with taiwanese 
taking to the streets to protest everything from prostitution to 
pollution 
by the following year it became apparent that the gradual 
liberalizing trend would not easily be reversed 
when chiang chingkuo died in january 1988 he was succeeded by 
vice president lee tenghui the first native taiwanese to lead the 
nationalist government and a supporter of democratic reform 
six months later lee was named chairman of the nationalist 
party and some but not all aging hardliners from the mainland 
retired from top party posts 
the nationalist leadership under lee has proposed a gradual 
increase in the percentage of the legislature that is elected on 
taiwan still only less than half the seats will be contested in 
dec 2 elections making it impossible for the opposition to wrest 
any real political power from the nationalists 
we are fully committed to democratization government 
spokesman shaw yuming said in a recent interview we are moving 
slowly but surely to meet the demands of the time 
but taiwan still has problems 
rising wages and an appreciating currency these have made 
taiwan less competitive in lowcost exports and the government is 
seeking a new economic formula to deal with the problem we must 
actively push forward the research of topnotch industrial 
technologies premier lee huan recently told the legislature 
the service sector should also grow quicker to become the center 
of our future economic development 
pollution caused by years of rapid development taipeis air is 
foul and the islands rivers are filthy some villagers have 
protested the construction of new factories they fear will ruin the 
local environment 
gambling and speculation gambling is illegal but rampant and 
speculating in the stock market has become the national pastime 
the taiwan stock exchange is second only to tokyos in trading 
volume and some analysts believe it is a speculative bubble 
waiting to burst some see the obsession as a temporary phenomenon 
following the easing of foreign exchange controls in 1987 others 
argue that industrialists are more interested in quick profit than 
in longterm investment such as automating factories and developing 
more sophisticated products 
perhaps the greatest challenge facing taiwan is its policy 
toward mainland china 
official policy remains the three nos no contact no 
negotiations no compromise with the communists but that policy 
today is a shambles 
the government allows trade with the mainland if conducted 
through a third party such as hong kong and taiwanese businessmen 
have begun investing in the mainland to take advantage of low labor 
costs 
finance minister shirley kuo traveled to beijing in may to 
attend an asian development bank meeting and met privately with 
communist officials 
the future of such contacts is somewhat clouded because of the 
communists violent suppression of the democracy movement this past 
spring but the old nationalist dream of returning to rule the 
mainland seems shattered 
when the chinese communist government seemed in disarray during 
the spring democracy movement the nationalists were forced to 
acknowledge there was not much they could do but watch 
we must have the courage to face the fact that at this moment 
we are unable to effectively exercise the right to govern the 
mainland president lee told a meeting of nationalist leaders on 
june 3 
