remember the bachelor mother kind of movie in which ginger 
rogers seeks a husband so her baby will have a father 
look whos talking is a 1989 replay with all the old 
gimmicks intact i dont like to fly she insists next scene 
shes flying in his plane the only innovation the baby talks 
not only that the voice is that of bruce willis the title get it 
its a pleasant sitcom with amiable performances especially by 
the four infants who play mikey the scenes under the titles will 
no doubt arouse controversy a large round object floats amid 
translucent undulating folds of matter bouncing gently at the 
bottom of a pit a flock of flittering chattering polliwogs enters 
the space and one of them joyfully discovers the round object and 
climbs inside a new kind of sex education 
throughout the film the voice of willis makes comments 
enjoying his ninemonth swim complaining about his abrupt 
emergence conversing with other infants and generally observing 
the human comedy the oneliners wear thin but some of it is funny 
stuff 
mikeys mother is kirstie alley a thirtysomething accountant 
who has been impregnated by her client a lecherous charmless 
fastfood entrepreneur george segal when she goes into labor 
she hails a new york cab driven by john travolta who races her to 
the hospital then dons a mask and gown and witnesses the delivery 
as you can guess he falls for kirstie and her baby but she 
considers him a loser he becomes the sitter while she prowls for 
prospective fathers not realizing that travolta is really a 
struggling flight instructor to illustrate his compassion there 
is a subplot about his concern for his senile grandfather abe 
vigoda 
amy heckerling fast times at ridgemont high directed her 
own script a loose affair that allows the actors to ad lib 
aimlessly the veracity of the film was not helped by filming it in 
canada the producers saved money but theres no way that 
vancouver can double for manhattan 
kirstie alley manages an endearing portrait of the beleaguered 
mother shes as appealing on the big screen as she is in 
cheers travolta is so laid back that he seems invisible at 
times but its good to see him back olympia dukakis has some 
bright moments as the worrying grandmother 
look whos talking is a tristar release produced by 
jonathan d krane the rating is pg13 mostly for adult 
situations running time 103 minutes 
