<TEXT>
money matters to terry mcmillan but the author 
doesnt yearn for luxury hotels or billiondollar deals just 
simple things a nice apartment or a good movie 
the characters in her second novel disappearing acts 
viking 1895 think a lot about money too franklin works off 
and on as a construction worker zora is a school teacher dreaming 
of making it as a singer and songwriter 
theyre two warm intelligent people living in brooklyn who meet 
by accident and fall in love but if savings are low luck matters 
and franklin and zora are nearly destroyed by events theyre 
incapable of controlling 
she loves franklin mcmillan said thats the whole point 
of the story how much is enough how much do you give before you 
say i cant do this anymore 
its like real life every relationship starts out great and 
then reality sets in and there are things you have to deal with a 
lot of it boils down to how much of an investment youre willing to 
make in order to make a marriage or whatever work 
the novel is a tapestry of exits and entrances disappearances 
and reappearances franklins moods fluctuate like the dow jones 
average ranging from playfulness to selfpity and violence zora 
hiding a case of epilepsy she fears will drive her man away 
juggles career and family finding release in music friends and 
the son conceived with franklin 
the title of the book came to me in a dream mcmillan said 
i was in brooklyn and i knew i wanted to tell the story about 
what can happen between a man and a woman when they fall in love 
and all these other things happen 
i was in a similar situation where i couldnt believe i had 
arrived at this point i stopped seeing my friends i stopped going 
to certain places because he wasnt interested i just disappeared 
i went to sleep and when i woke up that morning i said 
disappearing acts 
mcmillan lets franklin and zora tell their own stories trading 
chapters between the two she began with the names originally 
wanting to call franklin langston after author and poet 
langston hughes and zora mona 
but somehow franklin with its soft first syllable running 
into the hard k and gently trailing off again fit the 
powerful sensitive man tortured by his inability to find steady 
work 
and the sophisticated but streetwise woman he alternately loves 
and torments was renamed zora in honor of the great writer zora 
neale hurston 
the voices followed franklins earthy and angry tender and 
romantic a selfeducated black man trying to win zoras trust 
while battling a racist society and his own feelings of inadequacy 
his voice is mirrored in the following passage 
i could see that she was a little scared at first i mean 
sparks was flying so fast and everything and i was just waiting 
for her to tell me that her heart had been broke so many times she 
didnt trust men no more i was all set to tell her this time 
baby dont be scared this man aint interested in breaking your 
heart hes interested in gluing it back together and keeping it 
for hisself 
zoras voice is hopeful and frightened shes smart enough to 
know what she wants but too dependent on franklin to contend with 
his bitterness and physical power 
one of the things ive loved about franklin from the start is 
how safe he makes me feel protected im not even talking about 
his job situation im talking about his heart when he puts his 
arms around me if the wind was blowing a hundred miles an hour i 
wouldnt know it one thing im sure of when god made him he 
shouldve been cloned more women need to feel like this 
zora was harder for mcmillan to write than franklin i wanted 
her to have some street smarts but i didnt want her to be one of 
these prissy smith college types the author said 
there are a lot of educated black people who sound white i 
didnt want her to sound like that theres a rhythm to her 
sentences 
much of mcmillans childhood can be traced by reading her first 
novel mama she grew up in a poor section of point haven 
mich but escaped to the sunshine and promise of california as a 
teenager in the late 1960s a love affair at 18 inspired her to 
write poetry and soon mcmillan was writing vignettes 
she attended the university of california at berkeley joining a 
fiction workshop run by novelist and poet ishmael reed who 
encouraged mcmillan to tap her writing talents 
it was so easy so gratifying said mcmillan who now lives 
in tucson ariz not to say i actually wrote and finished real 
stories but the whole thing was emerging and it was just 
wonderful 
vignettes soon gave way to short stories and one short story 
gave way to mama published in 1985 mcmillan needed just two 
weeks to write the books first draft and another two weeks to 
complete the second 
my mother raised a houseful of kids sort of alone and i 
think she did a good job of it she said i couldnt figure out 
how she did it it was more of an exploration or a recounting of 
where she got her strength from 
mama was autobiographical and so is disappearing acts 
when i say autobiographical i mean being able to relate and 
identify with things that i have witnessed seen observed or 
experienced or a combination of all of them 
</TEXT>
