<DOCNO> AP891002-0287 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
husbands and wives struggling with the 
staggering costs of nursing home care for a spouse have new 
protections against the threat of poverty under rules that kick in 
this month as part of the medicare catastrohic health insurance 
program 
the spousal impoverishment rules have broad support on 
capitol hill and appear safe from repeal as congress debates 
whether to scrap major provisions of the catastrophiccare package 
to appease senior citizens angry at the costs of the coverage 
the new nursing home protections most typically will benefit 
older women who might otherwise be left destitute when their 
husbands are institutionalized at costs averaging more than 25000 
a year advocates say 
in the past medicaid would help pay nursing home bills only 
after couples spent most assets and income of the institutionalized 
spouse often leaving the athome spouse little to live on 
it was really a very tragic situation said laura loeb of 
the older womens league with women living on average about 
eight years longer than men these older women were forced to live 
out their remaining years in poverty 
attorney patricia nemore of the national senior citizens law 
center said that if most of a couples assets and income were 
listed in the name of the spouse who went into the nursing home 
you could lose pretty much everything 
some couples were driven to divorce to establish courtordered 
property and income rights for the noninstitutionalized spouse 
a 1987 congressional study found that the high costs of 
nursinghome care were quickly exhausting many couples resources 
leaving more than half of all couples impoverished within six 
months after one spouse entered a nursing home about 15 percent of 
the nations 15 million nursing home residents are married 
most often it is the wife who remains in the community and 
she often is left with little or no money with which to meet her 
own health care and other needs the senate special committee on 
aging reported last year 
under rules that took effect sept 30 and being implemented by 
states this month the spouse in the community will be able to keep 
more of the couples combined assets and income 
where couples in the past could qualify for medicaid help only 
after spending all but about 20003000 in assets other than 
their homes and certain personal belongings now they will be able 
to keep 1200060000 depending on the level set by their state 
the minimum monthly income allowed in the past was set at the 
supplemental security income level 368 in 1989 but now rises to 
122 percent of poverty or 815 and will increase to 133 percent 
in july 1991 and 150 percent in july 1992 states will be allowed 
to let couples keep up to 1500 a month in 1989 with the maximum 
rising in future years 
income and asset limits could be even higher if ordered by the 
courts 
ronald pollack executive director of families usa an advocacy 
group for the elderly said that while the new protection doesnt 
solve the problem of rising costs for longterm care it 
certainly provides tremendous relief 
for somebody who has lived relatively well the amount they 
can keep still may be seen as a hardship but for those of moderate 
to middle income it is going to substantially improve the 
protection that they had before pollack said 
the health care financing administration has estimated that in 
fiscal 1990 the new protections will cost the federal government 
165 million and state governments 135 million the federal share 
will rise to 245 million in 1991 and the state share to 200 
million 
john rother legislative director for the american association 
of retired persons said the costs are a drop in the bucket yet 
produce a benefit that is a real lifesaver for many older 
americans 
it doesnt do anything for the person without a spouse but it 
does protect many of the people whove sacrificed the most 
husbands and wives who already have spent years taking care of a 
spouse at home rother said 
the new impoverishment rules were enacted as part of a program 
to insure the elderly against the costs of catastrophic illness 
but even before all the programs benefits have taken effect many 
senior citizens are demanding its repeal because they say it is too 
costly 
congress is expected to scrap much of the program or cut it 
back but even legislators leading the call for repeal favor 
preserving the new impoverishment rules as a worthwhile and 
inexpensive protection 
advocates for the elderly meanwhile say that even if the whole 
catastrophic program survives the nation still needs a solution to 
the high costs of longterm care largely overlooked in the package 
spousal impoverishment is a result of the fact that our health 
care system doesnt cover these costs said ms loeb we still 
need some sort of public program that provides protection for the 
really catastrophic costs of nursing and home health care 
