agreement has received the necessary backing of importing and 
exporting nations allowing it to take effect without new 
provisions for price supports officials said monday 
the announcement by the international coffee organization 
coincided with the resumption of talks among coffeetrading nations 
aimed at reopening negotiations on a replacement accord 
some 41 exporting and 18 importing countries have notified the 
united nations that they accept the extended coffee agreement said 
alexandre beltrao the coffee organizations executive director 
the backers include brazil colombia the ivory coast mexico 
el salvador indonesia uganda and all other key exporters 
the united states the world biggest importer all members of 
the european community canada switzerland and japan have also 
accepted the extended agreement 
the agreement maintains the international coffee organization as 
a forum for discussing matters of mutual concern to exporters and 
importers including the shape of any possible new agreement on 
quotas 
