<TEXT>
the man picked to head the securities and 
exchange commission believes he can fight to keep the nations 
stock markets honest but that its up to the industry to woo back 
small investors 
richard c breeden replying at length monday to a series of 
written questions from the senators who will vote on his 
appointment said restoring investor confidence in the wake of the 
1987 crash and the insider trading scandals is a job for the 
securities industry itself 
many americans may also have a perception that selfinterest 
and corruption among securities industry participants are 
widespread said breeden in the 109page questionandanswer 
sheet 
the commission can help correct this perception through 
vigorous enforcement but much of this change must be accomplished 
by the industry itself through renewed attention to retail 
customers and dedication to ethical business practices 
breeden also said that the head of the sec does not have the 
authority on his own to halt trading in the midst of a disaster 
such as the 1987 crash and even if he did i would not consider 
such a step 
breeden said that theres too much uncertainty about when the 
markets would close and for how long 
in a crisis this uncertainty and the related rumors 
concerning its likelihood could have seriously adverse 
consequences 
breeden 37 a key white house aide was nominated by president 
bush in august to succeed sec chairman david s ruder who returned 
to teaching law last week 
the senate has yet to confirm breeden the assistant to the 
president for issue analysis and the chief white house liaison on 
the recent savings and loan bailout bill 
breeden received a warm reception last month at his confirmation 
hearing before the senate banking housing and urban affairs 
committee a committee vote is expected later this month 
in the meantime sec member edward h fleischman has been tapped 
as acting sec chairman until the breeden nomination is decided 
breeden said in the written response that he believes vigorous 
enforcement of existing rules against insider trading and other 
illegal activities is one of the most effective means to increase 
individual investor confidence and participation 
he added that his experience with the sampl restructuring has 
largely confirmed my prior views rather than changing them about 
strict enforcement of safety and soundness standards 
on other topics breeden said he 
believed securities laws would benefit from modernization 
because current law often excessively restricts competition 
doesnt think the rival commodity futures trading commission 
should have exclusive control over all hybrid financial 
products that have some characteristics of securities and futures 
contracts because it could stifle innovation 
favors breaking down the glasssteagall acts barrier between 
commerical banking and the securities industry but only if the 
entire regulatory structure that would replace it was adequate 
to protect the integrity of the securities markets 
</TEXT>
